    title: "When AI commoditises research, point of view is the only moat left",
    dek: "In a market where every team accesses the same models and the same data, the differentiator is a clear position your product stands for that AI can't generate. Most products don't have one.",
    author: "Genesis",
    date: "May 22, 2026",
    read: 6,
    feature: false,
    sourceUrl: "https://www.greenbook.org/insights/artificial-intelligence-and-machine-learning/in-the-age-of-ai-point-of-view-is-the-only-moat-left",
    sourceLabel: "Greenbook",
    tweet: "AI commoditises research. It commoditises execution. It doesn't commoditise a genuine, defensible point of view. Most products don't have one — and now that gap shows. https://productgenesis.ai/#post-s13",
    body: [
      "The traditional competitive advantages in AI-saturated markets are collapsing faster than most product teams have acknowledged. Norbert Sari's analysis identifies the specific mechanisms: proprietary datasets are no longer defensible because AI can synthesize comparable signals from public sources, and 'full-service' positioning signals commoditisation rather than competence to buyers who now arrive with 83% of their purchase requirements already defined before contacting a salesperson.",
      "The AI infrastructure bet fails for the same reason. Gartner projects that over 80% of enterprises will have used GenAI APIs in production environments in 2026. When your differentiator is accessible to every competitor with a credit card, it's table stakes. What AI cannot replicate is a genuine, intellectually defensible point of view: a specific stance on how markets function, what the right approach to a problem is, and why your methodology produces better outcomes than the alternatives.",
      "A strong POV does concrete commercial work. It creates pricing power — clients who agree with your worldview don't negotiate on price because they're not comparing you to alternatives with the same premise. It simplifies messaging — all your content, positioning, and sales material flows from one central idea rather than a feature matrix. And it filters: the POV attracts aligned clients while repelling mismatches, shortening sales cycles and reducing churn from customers whose expectations were never aligned with your actual approach.",
      "For AI product teams specifically, the POV question is urgent. In a market where every product claims similar model access, similar speed improvements, and similar accuracy benchmarks, what your product believes — about how the problem should be solved, what trade-offs are worth making, what the user actually needs — is the only thing that can't be copied in a sprint. Most products don't have a genuine POV. They have a positioning statement. The gap between those two things is the gap between a defensible product and a feature.",
    ],
